Civil rights group warns against travel to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people traveling to Missouri about the state&#39;s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group&#39;s statement read: &quot;The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, in effect until August 28, 2017, urges all African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to exercise extra caution and extreme caution when traveling throughout the state, given the spate of suspicious racially motivated incidents that has recently taken place across the state and is also highlighted here.&quot;
The NAACP said the group&#39;s travel warning was prompted by a recent Missouri law that makes it harder to win discrimination lawsuits and the fact that minorities are disproportionately targeted by law enforcement in the state.
&quot;People&#39;s civil rights are being violated.
They&#39;re pulled over to the side of the road because of the color of their skin, they&#39;re beaten or killed,&quot; Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri branch of the NAACP, told The Kansas City Star.
&quot;We&#39;ve never had so many complaints before.&quot;
This is the first such warning the organization has issued for a US state.
The group cited events such as racist insults directed at black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while driving through the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
In addition, the note cites a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General showing that black drivers are 75% more likely to have their cars pulled over than white drivers in the state.
&quot;The notice is for people to be aware and to warn their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri,&quot; Chapel said.
&quot;People need to be prepared, whether that means bringing bail money or letting relatives know they&#39;re going through the state.&quot;
According to the most recent data from the FBI&#39;s Hate Crimes Reporting Program, 100 hate crimes were documented in Missouri in 2015, which ranks the state 16th nationally for similar offenses.
The travel warning also comes in response to a new law in Missouri that makes it harder to sue a company for discrimination in the search for housing or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel advisories for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration laws requiring local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations that the ACLU said increased racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently interest groups have begun to use the measure as a backlash against certain laws and trends within the United States.
Hepatitis: What should everyone know about the different forms of this serious disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different hepatitis viruses - A, B, C, D and E.
All these viruses cause acute inflammation of liver tissue.
Chronic hepatitis B and C, however, have a malignant course, which can further develop into liver cirrhosis, i.e. liver wrinkling and liver cancer.
Kuulo Kutsar, epidemiology advisor of the Health Board, says that the symptoms of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of liver inflammation - fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, grayish stool, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The popular name of liver inflammation, jaundice, also comes from the last symptom.
Hepatitis can be asymptomatic in children.
It is possible to determine different types of liver inflammation only on the basis of laboratory test data.
Acute hepatitis can turn into chronic hepatitis and go on for decades without symptoms, which means that a person may not know anything about their dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Kuulo Kutsar points out different forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis A viruses are spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, through sex, from the feces of an infected person to and from hands to food, surfaces, objects, mouth, and drug use.
The danger or risk group of hepatitis A infection includes family members and caregivers of the sick person, people with chronic liver diseases, people who have sex with an infected person, men who have sex with men, drug addicts, travelers visiting countries with a high prevalence of hepatitis A.
Infection can be prevented by vaccination, vaccination is especially recommended for people who travel a lot and are in the hepatitis A risk group.
In addition, daily compliance with hygiene requirements is important: wash or disinfect hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before eating them.
Hepatitis B viruses are spread by contact with the blood of a sick person, injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated household items (toothbrushes, shaving tools), donor blood, sex with a person suspected of hepatitis, and from a mother with hepatitis to a fetus/newborn.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug users, sex partners of an infected person, men who have sex with men, newborns of an infected mother, sick family members and caregivers, healthcare workers, rescue workers and police officers who come into contact with blood and other body fluids, and travelers visiting countries with a high incidence of hepatitis B.
It is possible to vaccinate people to prevent hepatitis B; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people belonging to the risk group, as well as people suffering from chronic liver diseases, people with HIV infection, sexually transmitted diseases and people with diabetes.
Other preventive measures for hepatitis B are: avoiding the use of unfamiliar hygiene and manicure tools, other sharp tools and syringes and needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of a condom during sex with a risk of infection or avoiding risky sexual behavior.
Hepatitis B vaccination is part of the national immunization program in Estonia and is free for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are spread by contact with the blood of a sick person, injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using household items contaminated with blood, donor blood, sex with a person suspected of hepatitis, and from a mother with hepatitis to a fetus/newborn.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug users, sex partners of an infected person, men who have sex with men, newborns of an infected mother, sick family members and caregivers, healthcare workers, rescue workers and police officers who come into contact with blood and other body fluids, people with HIV infection, and visitors to countries with a high incidence of hepatitis C. passengers.
Hepatitis C prevention measures include: refraining from the use of unfamiliar hygiene and manicure products, other sharp tools and syringes, needles, tattooing and piercing, and the use of a condom during sex with a risk of infection.
There is no vaccine against hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which multiplies in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Therefore, hepatitis D infection occurs together with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
Hepatitis D viruses are spread through contact with blood and other body fluids, contaminated syringes and needles, sexual contact, and rarely from an infected mother to the fetus.
The risk group for hepatitis D is chronic hepatitis B virus carriers and people who do not have immunity against hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with the hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects a person from infection with the hepatitis D virus.
Hepatitis E viruses are spread through the fecal-oral route through drinking water and food, including eating undercooked meat, fish, and shellfish, donor blood, shared syringes, and from an infected mother to a fetus.
Travelers can become infected with hepatitis E in countries with a high incidence of hepatitis E.
Hepatitis E prevention measures include compliance with hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after caring for the sick.
Wash fruits and vegetables before consumption, avoid eating undercooked meat, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water and refrain from using drugs.
