Despite the title, Anne-Marie O&#39;Connor&#39;s &quot;The Lady in Gold. The Extraordinary Story of Gustav Klimt&#39;s Masterpiece, Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer&quot; delves much deeper into the cultural life of late 19th and early 20th century Vienna than the story of the birth of a work of art.
But even more thoroughly into history.
The awe-inspiring amount of information would have been wasted, perhaps a harder pruning axe, a narrower topic would have allowed the extraordinary story of the portrait promised in the title to gain more influence.
Currently, it is as if there are two books between the same covers: the story of Gustav Klimt and Adele Bloch-Bauer depicted in his painting &quot;Lady in Gold&quot; and a much larger and more comprehensive history book about respectable Jewish families and the German occupation with its consequences in Austria.
The first third of the book takes you in the middle of the bubbling cultural life of Vienna, and anyone who has been to the Austrian capital can easily imagine how life was around the Ringstrasse more than a hundred years ago, or how everyone in the Central cafe turned their heads when Klimt walked in.
The concentration of cultural figures was high in one of Europe&#39;s richest cities, and seeing a familiar name in a book makes you feel a little more cultured.
At the same time, for example, the fact that Sigmund Freud worked in a city where incurable syphilis was rampant and had the highest suicide rate in Europe seems to add nothing to the development of the story.
Or maybe still - every brushstroke in a couple of sentences adds color to the cultural life in Vienna at the beginning of the 20th century.
Dream of a trip to the Soviet Union
In the last decades of the 19th century, the number of Jews in Vienna had exploded, becoming the largest Jewish community in Western Europe.
At the turn of the century, almost every tenth resident of Vienna was Jewish.
Adele&#39;s parents were also newcomers to Vienna, but by the time Adele married the Czech sugar tycoon Ferdinand Bloch twice before her and posed for Klimt for his famous paintings, her father&#39;s bank had already become the seventh largest bank in the Habsburg Empire.
But Adele was not attracted by all the glamorous life she belonged to.
If you look at &quot;The Lady in Gold&quot;, it is hard to believe that towards the end of her life this magnificent lady was infected with socialism and dreamed of a trip to the Soviet Union.
By 1903, when Ferdinand Bloch decided to commission a portrait of his wife from Klimt, the latter was the hottest painter in Vienna.
Klimt&#39;s order cost 4,000 kroons at that time, a quarter of the price of a well-located country house.
The sugar tycoon was not deterred by the suspicion of the master&#39;s affair with the model in some of the portraits.
As for Adele, the only certain fact is that the close relationship between the model and the artist, formed during the work, continued until the end of her life.
Anne-Marie O&#39;Connor - &quot;The Lady in Gold.&quot;
The Extraordinary Story of Gustav Klimt&#39;s Masterpiece, Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer&quot;, Varrak 2016, translated from English by Aldo Randmaa.
Just before starting work with Adele, Klimt had visited the Basilica of San Vitale in Ravenna, and researchers believe that it was the brilliant mosaics of Empress Theodora that he saw there that gave the artist the idea to make a golden portrait of Adele as a painted mosaic.
Klimt presented his &quot;Lady in Gold&quot; in Vienna in 1908 and around the same time (1907-1908) another golden painting &quot;The Kiss&quot; was born.
Art historians did not miss the similarity between the two women.
How is Hitler involved in the story?
&quot;I think that in memory of my friend Klimt, I owe him to make his handiwork available to the public,&quot; Adele Bloch-Bauer wrote to the director of the Belvedere Museum a few years after the artist&#39;s death (Klimt died in February 1918) and wanted their family&#39;s Klimt collection to go to the museum .
Six years before his death, Klimt had completed another portrait of Adele.
Also in her will (Adele died in February 1925), she asked that her husband leave her two portraits and four Gustav Klimt landscape paintings to the Austrian Gallery.
He bequeathed his jewelry to his nieces Maria and Luise.
A year after Klimt finished the &quot;Austrian Mona Lisa&quot;, 17-year-old Adolf Hitler tried to enter the Vienna Academy of Fine Arts, but failed the drawing exam.
Although Hitler&#39;s later anti-Semitism is sometimes attributed to his rejection of Jewish professors at the academy, none of his examiners were actually Jewish.
In any case, the task of the Austrian Gallery referred to in Maria&#39;s will had changed considerably by 1939 - it had become important to find works of interest to the Nazi Party from Vienna&#39;s rich Jewish art collections.
Some works in Adele&#39;s home also fit into Hitler&#39;s personal art collection, but not Klimt&#39;s.
Sixty years after the Nazi art heist, a ten-year legal battle between the Austrian government and the heirs of the Bloch-Bauers began.
At this point, it should only be noted that while &quot;The Kiss&quot; can be seen at the Belvedere Palace in Vienna, &quot;The Lady in Gold&quot; depicting Adele Bloch-Bauer must be seen at the Neue Galerie in New York.
And read the aforementioned book before going to Vienna.
Even if you don&#39;t plan on going to see Klimt&#39;s work, because at least my emotions after closing the book revolved more around Nazis and Jews than the $135 million painting and model Adele Bloch-Bauer.
So not so much a portrait, but rather a story of the family&#39;s fate - and a very touching story.
The family tree of the Bauers mentioned at the beginning of the book noticeably facilitated orientation in the events.
