Blocking critics from Facebook - Don&#39;t run for public office if you can&#39;t stand criticism from voters
The father of our country knew a lot about adverse media coverage.
Americans loved George Washington, but it didn&#39;t take long for newspapers to vilify him for everything from his domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism naturally irritated him.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said that &quot;freedom of speech may be taken from us, and dumb and silent we may be led like sheep to the slaughter.&quot;
Which brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who is struggling to be more like Washington.
Hogan&#39;s subordinates have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And towards the beginning of the week, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) sued him because of it.
The governor&#39;s staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and online comments swarmed with &quot;Who cares?&quot;-style backlash.
&quot;It&#39;s just Facebook,&quot; many said.
But it does count.
And that counts especially when it&#39;s a guy like Hogan.
This is an incredibly popular Republican governor in an overwhelmingly Democratic state.
His approval rating ranks second best among the nation&#39;s 50 governors.
Hogan is not a hothead who reacts without thinking.
He has ruled the state with a firm hand and has remained firm on his principles.
In addition, he has used Facebook quite adeptly as the main tool to communicate with his constituents, for example, cheerfully presenting his bald head for the first time after chemotherapy.
So blocking people visiting the governor&#39;s page — which is an officially labeled public forum run by staff paid by taxpayer dollars — is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan&#39;s spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor&#39;s behavior, saying the blocking of comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it&#39;s too easy to paint a picture of internet trolls, spammers or angry people on the web.
The Post spoke with several real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And that&#39;s exactly what they are - real people communicating with their elected leaders. A teacher, business owner and pastor, not internet trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not at all rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, emphasizing Hogan&#39;s Catholicism.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland, did not incite hate, but actual hate crimes.
&quot;I politely commented that I was disappointed that he had not responded to the hate crimes or other recent news,&quot; he wrote in the comments section of The Post&#39;s news story.
&quot;I also don&#39;t like the idea that when a lot of people are commenting on the same issue, some of them call it a collective effort instead of recognizing that it&#39;s a large number of concerned citizens.&quot;
What the governor&#39;s staff called a &quot;targeted spam attack&quot; others would probably call &quot;public support.&quot;
The age of Facebook makes it easy to match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It&#39;s a lot cleaner than in the old days, when you had to send out workers to collect critical editorials and burn them, or arrest protesters and silence them.
But that&#39;s exactly what&#39;s happening right now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for making Facebook and other social media outlets toothless.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first landmark rulings on this issue was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris ruled in Alexandria that the chairwoman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment when she blocked a voter from her Facebook page.
In Kentucky, the ACLU also went after Gov. Matt Bevin (R) over his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn&#39;t be that hard.
In Washington&#39;s time, affordable postage had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous letter writers ridiculed his leadership style.
And even then, Washington had to deal with anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under pseudonyms such as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, trashing Washington&#39;s decisions.
His cabinet was buried under petitions criticizing his views on friendship, trade and shipping treaties with Britain, according to historical documents compiled by the online Project to Collect George Washington&#39;s Letters.
But he did not force them to be silent.
Freedom of speech, dissent and debate are the cornerstones of our country.
And good leadership means accepting it.
