Poverty and death in Indonesia&#39;s gold-rich land
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn&#39;t use the stove.
He rarely even uses the potty.
In a wooden hut in Enarotal, the capital of Paniai regency in Indonesia&#39;s recalcitrant Papua province, a housewife places a sweet potato, called nota in the local language, directly on the stove.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed from the heat and eagerly poked into the skin with unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the mud floor - he has no furniture - and it&#39;s also where he does his daily chores, such as washing clothes with murky water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room plays the role of a toilet.
Being the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives, she is not assigned to tend any of the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
However, working late can be dangerous - most of the men in the village are unemployed and many of them drink heavily, and there are also soldiers here.
&quot;No one dares to walk around the village after five o&#39;clock in the evening,&quot; he says.
This is a rare glimpse into life in the highlands of Papua. It is a former Dutch colony that was incorporated into Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which just 1,026 elderly people were forced to vote by raising their hands in front of occupying forces.
The movement, which had been calling for liberation from Dutch rule, quickly turned its fury against the Jakarta government, which still maintains its tight grip on the region, shutting out foreign journalists and human rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, leaving independent Papua New Guinea with the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is both a remote and desolate place. Getting here requires a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire, followed by a nauseating five-hour journey by rental car.
There is no public transport.
With a population of about 19,000, the town consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and covered by corrugated iron roofs that rust has turned to various shades of yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made the journey here, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners have visited.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Papuans of Mee Pago worshiped a god called Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
&quot;We weren&#39;t used to wearing clothes like this,&quot; says Degei, referring to her colorful handwoven turban, dark blouse and bright skirt.
&quot;Before that, we only wore plant leaves on our bodies.&quot;
Papua is Indonesia&#39;s poorest province, with 28% of people living below the poverty line and infant mortality and illiteracy statistics among the worst in Asia.
But it is also a land rich in gold in Indonesia.
Just 100 km from Pania, a mountainous province about the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000, is the world&#39;s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about US$3.1 billion worth of gold and copper from here.
In addition, Papua boasts timber reserves estimated to be worth US$78 billion.
But these riches are a source of suffering for Papuans because they provide the suffocating presence of the powerful Indonesian military.
A 2005 investigation by The New York Times found that Freeport paid local military personnel and military units approximately US$20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to US$150,000 per officer.
Papuan aspirations for greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are dealt with mercilessly.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the mass killings in the 1970s in Papua&#39;s tribal highlands amounted to genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
The Archdiocese of Birsbane&#39;s 2016 report &#39;We&#39;re Losing Everything&#39; includes evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (rape and electric shocks are particularly common, according to another report) and the brutal suppression of peaceful protests.
&quot;It&#39;s hard to count the number of victims because these kinds of incidents happen every week,&quot; says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened even more because Papua&#39;s natural resources have caused an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the province&#39;s 3.5 million residents are Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from Indonesia&#39;s populous islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese family restaurants sell gado-gado with crispy chicken and mixed vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals can&#39;t compete with them.
&quot;Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables at the traditional market cheaper than local Papuans,&quot; explains 24-year-old Abeth You, born in Pania, who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, for work.
&quot;Indigenous Papuans – the Papuan mama-mama [women] – are losing their market share as a result.&quot;
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised to address these inequalities and human rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter won 27 of Papua&#39;s 29 constituencies, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But very little has changed in Papua and the locals feel cheated.
&quot;Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 expecting him to fulfill our hopes for restoring justice,&quot; You says.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Paniai was struggling in a slump.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children were singing Christmas carols around a fire in Enarotal when two Indonesian soldiers appeared out of the darkness on a motorcycle.
The terrified children told them they should turn on their headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and witnesses, drunken soldiers chased the children and beat them with the handles of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so brutally that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby election commission building was set on fire, and things escalated further the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on the soccer field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua, which involved running around and imitating birdsong.
Some protesters started throwing stones at the police and military.
As resentment grew, an order was sent to the soldiers via internal radio. &quot;If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,&quot; the official document, seen by TIME magazine but not released to local media, said.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, an elder in Kego Koto district of Enarotali town, sensed the impending danger and appealed for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen.
&quot;As I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist,&quot; he told TIME magazine on the porch of his brightly colored treehouse.
Kayame still doesn&#39;t know who the shooter was, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
&quot;There were a lot of people, there were a lot of shots,&quot; he adds.
Local man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin who witnessed the shooting.
&quot;I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,&quot; Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME somberly.
&quot;I saw he was dead... I kissed him.&quot;
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his subordinates were only ensuring the security of their station because it had been attacked.
&quot;We have to defend ourselves when we are threatened with death,&quot; Papuan police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
&quot;It&#39;s a matter of life and death.&quot;
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many were injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura, offering condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the abuses in Papua.
&quot;I want to solve this case now so that it never happens again in the future,&quot; he said.
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would establish an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve the crimes against human rights that had occurred.
But apologies followed almost immediately.
“Most of the crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to solving these crimes, but we have to follow certain processes,&quot; he said.
However, speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, Wiranto took back his words, saying he had no intention of creating a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, &quot;everything will be resolved according to the law.&quot;
Wiranto, who has been accused by the United Nations of human rights crimes in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor during a bloody 1999 independence referendum, said 11 human rights crimes had already been resolved in Papua, including the one in Pania.
The families of Paniai&#39;s victims met such claims with grim disbelief.
&quot;I have been interrogated four times in the last three years, but there has been no progress,&quot; said Yohanes.
&quot;I&#39;m tired.&quot;
She says she still lives in fear years later.
&quot;I&#39;m afraid,&quot; he says.
&quot;I&#39;m afraid the military will arrest me, I&#39;m afraid I&#39;ll be shot.&quot;
His brother Yacobus confirmed the opinion that the people of Paniai are afraid to dissect the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
&quot;After the bodies were buried, the army came looking for me,&quot; he says.
The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in Deiyai, neighboring Paniai regency.
One person was killed and 17 injured, including children, when there was an argument between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to transport the unconscious man to the hospital.
The man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned in a nearby river while fishing, died on the way to hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company&#39;s office at the construction site.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at the policemen, to which the latter responded with warning shots.
But according to locals, the mobile brigade (Indonesian military police) started shooting at the crowd, killing one person.
&quot;We were in a big panic, we are afraid of retaliation,&quot; 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the injured being brought in, told TIME magazine.
&quot;I&#39;ve been hiding in my house for two days.&quot;
The Deiyai parliament has demanded the prosecution of the policemen involved and the withdrawal of the police mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development fuels the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dan and Damal tribes living in Papua&#39;s verdant central highlands.
Many of them have joined the Free Papua Movement (VPL), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by carrying out random attacks and kidnapping raids among Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the VPL are from Pania, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, the military has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of people in Pania over the past few years under the pretext of &quot;protecting the country&#39;s sovereignty&quot;.
Some of them never appear again.
Among the Papuan people, Pania is known as &quot;the tragic forgotten place&quot;.
Poverty breeds discontent.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotal is too expensive for the locals to buy.
Bread is just as unavailable.
People grow all their own food - mostly sweet potatoes, with some fruit and leafy greens.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can tend four or five sweet potato fields.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, and sell the rest at the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, the economic inequality between native Papuans and new migrants, who have arrived in large numbers since the opening of new flight routes to Nabire Airport, has deepened.
The few jobs that do exist go to better educated and wealthier migrants.
Papuans themselves often lack the capital or skills to run a competitive business.
&quot;Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there are no jobs or money here,&quot; says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
In addition, severe restrictions remain on foreign media.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were expelled from Papua for &quot;not following appropriate practices&quot;, despite being granted a rare filming permit.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy head of Human Rights Watch&#39;s Asia division, Jokowi&#39;s election promises to remove restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development have not been implemented.
&quot;In Indonesia, journalists trying to report from the easternmost restive provinces of Papua and West Papua face new threats of visa denial and blacklisting,&quot; he said in a statement.
The absence of a penetrating gaze from the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua&#39;s immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Belau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate &quot;various large-scale crimes&quot; in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have historically supported the VPL.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group&#39;s accusations, telling reporters in Jakarta: &quot;Indonesia still has a democratic system and freedom of the press, so it would be difficult to bury evidence of human rights violations.&quot;
Local people want more foreign governments to take notice.
When an official Dutch delegation, led by the country&#39;s human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local people broke their silence by imploring, &quot;We want freedom,&quot; according to a source present at the meeting who spoke on condition of anonymity.
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but Papuans do not think they will vote for Jokowi again.
&quot;Jokowi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people who are involved in the Paniai shooting,&quot; says tribal council chairman Hobai.
He wants to convey to Jokowi that, in addition to living under the constant threat of a predatory military, the people of Paniai are also languishing in poverty due to poor education and health services.
According to Gobai, the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, see their vote for Jokowi as a debt he has to pay.
&quot;They don&#39;t need money, they want justice,&quot; he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the Paniai shooting victims managed one last symbolic protest - they buried the body of one of the victims on land opposite the police station and the military base.
Knowing that justice may never be served, at least they don&#39;t let those responsible forget their crimes.
&quot;One of our family members was killed,&quot; Yacobus says with his head down.
&quot;What else could we do?&quot;
