The number of residence permit applicants increased dramatically during the Ukrainian crisis - in 2014, 1,087 people received temporary residence permits, compared to 675 a year earlier.
According to Statistics Estonia, the number of Ukrainian citizens is growing the most in Estonia - last year, 850 more Ukrainian citizens arrived in Estonia than left.
&quot;The Ukrainian community has always been large in Estonia, and due to the difficult circumstances in the country, it is natural that work and study opportunities are sought in a country where the community and, for many, also the family, are already in front of them&quot;, stated the spokesperson of the Ministry of the Interior, Kristin Rammus.
Last year and the year before last, the number of Ukrainians who received a temporary residence permit was even greater than the number of Russian citizens, although in ten years the largest number of temporary residence permits have been issued to the latter.
While Ukrainians mostly come here to work, Russian citizens come here for family migration.
&quot;Considering the historical Russian community here, they are more likely to have the largest family ties with people living in Russia,&quot; said Helina Maasing, a migration researcher at the Internal Defense Academy.
&quot;If you look at where Russian citizens who have received an Estonian residence permit have moved to live, Ida-Virumaa is right after Harjumaa&quot;, he added and pointed out that about 40 percent of them have married a citizen of the European Union.
Last year, 1,696 Russian citizens received a temporary residence permit, which is also a record number.
At the same time, the number of Russians who wanted to extend their residence permit decreased.
&quot;The jump is due to the fact that instead of extending the residence permit, a new residence permit has been applied for permanently settling in Estonia,&quot; explained Rammus, the spokesperson of the Ministry of the Interior, according to whom Russian citizens&#39; interest in the Estonian residence permit has remained rather stable for years.
Foreigners who have lived here for at least three years can apply for a new residence permit to permanently settle in Estonia from the previous year.
Its purpose is to encourage people who have adapted to stay here.
However, the residence permit of a long-term resident requires, for example, five years.
Because of the new residence permit, the extension of the old residence permit has apparently also decreased.
For example, last year such a residence permit was granted to 146 Ukrainians who have worked here for at least three years.
Now, Ukrainians can change jobs, and the Estonian state will no longer check whether the salary criterion has been met.
This residence permit became very popular - applicants last year included gray passport holders (1029), Russians (487), Indians (54) and Nigerians (36).
In total, 1,968 people received residence permits for the purpose of settling in Estonia, among them, for example, 23 Americans, 12 Egyptians, 18 Georgians and the same number of Chinese.
In the first half of this year, the total number of such applicants is already 1,269.
In ten years, surprisingly, Nigeria has become a country whose citizens are among the most active applicants for Estonian residence permits.
While three residence permits were issued to Nigerians in 2007, 200 last year.
People come from Nigeria to study at the universities here.
Estonian universities are also popular among, for example, Georgians, Chinese and Turks.
The number of citizens of India, Bangladesh and Nigeria has increased mainly due to educational migration.
In their case, too, the rule applies that where a community has already formed, it is easier for others to join,&quot; added Rammus.
In the course of ten years, two people have moved to Estonia from, for example, North Korea, the same number from Laos and Madagascar.
Ten people have come here from Cuba, 231 from South Korea, 40 from Indonesia and four from Uruguay.
If approximately 6,000 third-country nationals receive a residence permit per year, this is approximately 0.46 percent of the entire population.
Even if you add the citizens of the European Union, migration remains at around one percent&quot;, Maasing commented that the numbers are actually small.
According to the statistics office, a total of 14,822 people immigrated to Estonia last year, while 13,792 left here.
This means that immigration exceeded emigration for the second year running.
Most of the people moving out and moving in are Estonian citizens, but there are more of them among those leaving.
Therefore, the migration balance of Estonian citizens was in the red by 2,000 people last year.
Estonians mainly travel between Finland and Estonia.
