The new results of age assessment tests for Swedish asylum seekers were published
In Sweden, a test was conducted among asylum seekers, during which their age was assessed medically with a new approach. The most recent results of the test show that more than 80 percent of those tested were judged to be older than 18, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started the tests towards the beginning of this year.
The tests were created to more accurately assess age during the asylum application process after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to correctly determine the age of a number of allegedly underage refugees.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Institute of Forensic Medicine has issued a total of 2,481 test results between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were judged to be 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the Institute of Forensic Medicine assessed that the subject &quot;may be 18 years of age or older.&quot;
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the person was &quot;probably younger than 18&quot;.
Tests are only used if a person&#39;s age is in doubt.
According to Johan Göransson, who works at the Institute of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent compared to those of the previous months.
&quot;We don&#39;t see a big difference compared to the statistics from previous months, the numbers are pretty consistent,&quot; he told The Local.
The fact that a large proportion of cases were judged to be older than 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers have lied about their age.
The institute released the results of 581 tests in May and said that in 442 cases &quot;there are indications that the subject is 18 years of age or older.&quot;
But when the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of these 581 tests, it was found that in 243 cases the person had directly stated that they would turn 18 this year.
This medical age-estimating method, which involves X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRIs of knee joints, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some quarters.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing people&#39;s biological maturity to determine whether they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
&quot;I&#39;ve had reason to think about it and I don&#39;t think the current measurement method should be used.
Determining biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can&#39;t say for sure, we shouldn&#39;t pretend we can,&quot; he told the Metro newspaper.
But Johan Göransson from the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: &quot;In general, it can be said that the risk of inaccurately classifying a child as an adult is small.
The risk is the highest, at around 10%, if the person is a little under 18.&quot;
