The electric car revolution will significantly change the demand for metals.
Who are the winners and losers?
Not only is the electric car revolution dramatically changing everything from the fuel market to infrastructure, it&#39;s also creating new winners and losers in the metals market.
While mining giants like Glencore can say they win in one place and lose in another, that doesn&#39;t help smaller mining companies.
Currently, Glencore earns from coal and oil, but in the future, in the age of electric cars, demand for cobalt, lithium, copper, aluminum and nickel will increase.
This year, the stakes for the spread of electric cars have been raised by decisions by the governments of the UK, France and Norway, which promise to ban the sale of new cars that use fossil fuels in the coming decades.
Therefore, Volvo has already announced that they plan to abandon the internal combustion engine, and Tesla will launch a cheaper Model 3 electric car.
Bloomberg New Energy Finance predicts that electric cars will outsell petroleum-based cars within two decades.
&quot;For some metals, it changes everything,&quot; Simona Gambranini, commodities analyst at Capital Economics, told Bloomberg.
We&#39;ve already seen a big impact on metals like cobalt and lithium, which have been in demand for years.
Electric cars contain about three times more copper than a conventional car, Glencore said.
Even more copper is needed in charging stations, which Exane BNP Paribas estimates will increase copper demand by around five percent by 2025.
The increase in demand for electric car batteries means additional demand for lithium, cobalt, graphite and manganese.
Glencore will benefit from the growing trend of electric cars from rising copper prices and from being the world&#39;s largest cobalt producer, Jefferies Group predicted.
Other winners from the EV boom include Freeport-McMoRan and First Quantum Minerals, according to the brokerage.
The market is already reacting to the changing trend.
This year, cobalt has risen in price by 70 percent on the London Metal Exchange.
Last year&#39;s price increase was 37 percent.
Copper has also become more expensive this year by 14 percent, mainly due to economic growth.
Shares in Glencore rose 20 percent in London, outpacing rivals Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billiton and Anglo American.
On the losing side are lead companies like Recyclex and Campine, which have to adapt to the new era.
The main end use of lead is in batteries that supply current to the starters of gasoline and diesel cars.
Electric cars use lithium-ion batteries.
&quot;This is a serious risk to lead demand unless some other purpose is found for it to overcome the decline in demand,&quot; said Michael Widmer, head of metals market analysis at Bank of America Merrill Lynch.
The effect of the unfolding trend has yet to be seen in the lead price movement.
Lead is up 17 percent this year, with it being the metal with the best rise in prices among the main industrial metals in London.
Investors see problems for the metal far into the future.
&quot;I&#39;m not sure it&#39;s that bad for lead because cheap oil keeps conventional cars competitive,&quot; said Herwig Schmidt, head of sales at metals brokerage Triland Metals.
When demand for lead falls, it happens slowly.
Maybe it will happen like that in about ten years.
In the meantime, however, tougher emissions standards will mean growing demand for hybrid cars that rely on advanced lead-based batteries for frequent engine starts, the International Lead and Zinc Research Organization estimates.
Light metals such as aluminum are replacing steel because a lighter car can travel further with less electricity.
This can explain the additional 1.6 million tons of aluminum mummy demand between 2013 and 2016.
This represents 2.7 percent of the total world aluminum production.
That trend is likely to worsen, Widmer said.
Aluminum has risen in price by 13 percent this year, as growing demand from car manufacturers has led to a market deficit.
Steelmakers don&#39;t sleep.
AK Steel Holding is partnering with General Motors to use nanotechnology to produce ultra-lightweight car bodies.
ArcelorMittal and Tata Steel Europe are also trying to develop a lighter alloy of steel to counter aluminum mummification.
&quot;High-strength steel should be the answer to this development,&quot; said Sylvain Brunet, analyst at Exane BNP Paribas.
Some progress is being seen in Europe.
The end of the oil era may also bring suffering to platinum.
Last year, about half of that precious metal was used in catalytic converters for diesel cars, metals refiner Johnson Matthey said.
&quot;Many commodities that are in high demand now, such as oil and platinum, may not be in high demand in the future,&quot; said Bernard Dahdah, commodities analyst at Natixis.
This does not mean that raw materials as a whole will become less important, but their importance will change over the course of 15 years.
Platinum manufacturers believe there will be continued demand for diesel hybrid cars.
Uncore CEO Marc Grynberg said hybrid cars will continue to outsell all-electric cars in 2025.
The big hope for platinum producers 10 years from now lies in hydrogen cell-based cars developed by Toyota Motor and Hyundai Motos, which rely on platinum to generate electricity from hydrogen.
So far, however, this technology has not yet proven itself commercially.
&quot;Diesel appears to be the clear loser on the road to electric cars,&quot; said Brunet of Exane BNP Paribas.
German automakers suffered a major setback in July when a Stuttgart court banned diesel use in the hometown of Mercedes-Benz and Porsche.
