Barcelona were paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to buy the Brazilian out of his contract, and Neymar&#39;s salary is set to reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar&#39;s move to the French club.
PSG will undoubtedly be able to shell out that kind of money to sign Neymar and add to their star-studded line-up, given that the team is funded by the ruling family of the Qatari powerhouse.
Clubs are allowed to spend heavily to recruit players, but must balance this with legitimate income streams that allow them to make ends meet in the football business.
FFP was founded by Michel Platini after he was elected UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs who go into deep debt in search of success are actually cheating and risk going bankrupt if the banks or owners withdraw their support.
Since 2011, FFP has focused on tracking clubs&#39; losses instead of their debts.
This change means that the business model first used by Roman Abramovich at Chelsea in 2003 - buy a club with potential and then spend heavily to improve the team and build a global brand - will be harder to implement.
During FFP&#39;s current three-year assessment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can incur losses of up to €30 million.
And despite Platini being ousted in disgrace from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin remains committed to reining in excess spending.
&quot;FFP is certainly not dead and we will certainly continue to strengthen these regulations in the future,&quot; Andrea Traverso, who oversees FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar&#39;s buyout clause in one lump sum, they are able to split the amount over the life of the contract for accounting purposes.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so it is possible to show the transfer fee for the next five years as an amount of 44.4 million euros per year.
In the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, PSG received the heaviest penalties along with Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City.
PSG was fined €60 million ($82 million at the time), later reduced to €20 million, and the club was required to field a Champions League squad for 2014-2015. 21 players instead of the usual 25 in the season.
UEFA is on the lookout for clubs who may try to outwit the financial regulators by inflating their income through companies linked to the club&#39;s owners.
A Qatari company can sponsor PSG, but if the value of the sponsorship is deemed to exceed standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to count as official income.
That&#39;s what happened in 2014 when UEFA ruled that the value of the Qatar Tourism Authority&#39;s support for PSG was inflated.
There has been talk that some of Neymar&#39;s PSG services could come through payments to the 2022 World Cup organizing committee from Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny Neymar could become a World Cup ambassador and say UEFA regulators could easily uncover such a maneuver.
PSG&#39;s previous penalties mean UEFA will be even more vigilant about any attempts to flout the rules.
People familiar with the situation said on Thursday that UEFA has not proactively discussed Neymar&#39;s transfer with PSG.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they are not authorized to discuss the PSG situation.
The latest published reports show that PSG earned in 2015-2016. in the season of more than 10 million euros in profit with a turnover of approximately 542.4 million euros.
The figures for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG are hoping Neymar&#39;s arrival will bode well for sponsorship deals, merchandising and shirt sales.
The club expects an increase in turnover of at least 30 percent in connection with the conclusion of the contract.
The Spanish league, clearly upset by the departure of one of football&#39;s biggest stars, tried to block Neymar&#39;s transfer, claiming that PSG were in breach of FFP.
&quot;This is a clear case of &#39;financial doping&#39; with the club and the country,&quot; La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, pointing out that PSG is mainly owned by Qatar.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports magnate, shares La Liga&#39;s stance that the state funds the club.
&quot;It is a consequence of ownership rights and it has completely changed the whole football landscape over the last 15 years,&quot; Wenger said on Thursday.
&quot;When the club is owned by the state, everything is possible.
It is very difficult to respect the financial rules of fair play, as the country may have other ways or other interests for such a big player to represent the country.&quot;
