50 years ago today: a hurricane-sized storm in Estonia that tore roofs and windows from houses.
The hurricane called the storm of the century, which raged on August 6 and 7, caused great damage especially to Läänemaa, Harjumaa and Raplamaa.
In North-West Estonia, the wind speed was over 30 m/s during those days.
My old man ran from one bending tree to another in the garden and tried to support them with his hands.
Everything was dark and rattling, like the end of the world.
In the background, the roofs were already flying off the houses, old lady Linda Kurova from Haapsalu recalled in an interview given to Eesti Loodus magazine in 2002.
Linda&#39;s husband saw the garden he had planted collapse.
But why are you supporting the trees with your hands, how can you withstand such a storm?
The sea came under the window, water splashed in from the windows,&quot; said Mrs. Linda, who lived on Kalda street in Haapsalu at the time.
The fact that the roads were full of trees and the roof of the railway station platform had blown 20-30 meters away, Linda, like most of the Haapsalu children, only saw the next morning.
According to the locals, the trees behind Paralepa were lying on the ground, some completely lying down, some in half.
Everything looked very depressing, the storm was going through the beautiful old trees with a rattle and crackle like a war.
Lääne-Virumaa was not particularly badly affected in the August storm of 1967 compared to Western Estonia, but the losses were also great there, the Virumaa Teataja wrote in 2007.
Haapsalu Castle Park and Padis Park were wiped out, but the parks in our area were also heavily damaged.
In Tallinn, the wind speed was measured up to 35 meters per second, or about 130 kilometers per hour.
At Merivälja in Tallinn, on the evening of August 6, a tiny tern had called out: &quot;Mother, mother!
The chickens are in the air and can&#39;t come down anymore!&quot;, Virumaa Teataja wrote.
The Põlli manor building in Viljandimaa was so destroyed during the storm that it was decided to demolish it later.
The constructions of the Türi ski jump hill did not withstand the August storm and were not restored later.
The Punane Täht newspaper wrote on August 12, 1967 that the cleaning of cities and settlements from fallen trees and their branches is progressing slowly, and residents could join in the cleaning work.
Cornfields were also badly damaged by the storm, and the newspaper declared that &quot;party organizations must act as encouragers and guides both in the clean-up work and in the harvest.&quot;
We can talk about hurricanes if the average wind speed exceeds 32.7 m/s.
The gusty wind record in Estonia has stood since November 2, 1969, when the wind speed was measured at Ruhnu at 48 m/s.
On the island of Vaindloo, the measuring instrument broke, so the strong wind speed measured there could not be accurately recorded.
The secret of clean bathing beaches: cleaning at night and bad beach weather
Colder summer weather also means less cleaning effort at Tallinn&#39;s bathing beaches.
&quot;If the weather is good, people are on the beach, and if it&#39;s not, there are no people either,&quot; says the beach cleaner.
Seagulls are screeching on Stroom beach in northern Tallinn.
They are offered melodious competition by a low-revving tractor plowing stripes on the beach.
In fact, the latter sifts through the sand at a depth of seven centimeters, picking up sea debris and debris left behind by people: bottle caps, cigarette butts and others.
People still come to the beach whether the water is warm or not.
When the weather is nice, people are on the beach, and when it&#39;s not, there aren&#39;t any people either,&quot; says Aleksandr Usov, manager of the beach cleaning works of the private company Haabersti Haldus.
It is 6:30 a.m. and the beach is being cleaned up bitterly, because by eight o&#39;clock the square must be ready for people.
Usov has been at the post since four o&#39;clock.
Apart from Stroom, he also keeps an eye on Pirita, Harku lake, Kakumäe and Paljasaare&#39;s Pikakar beach.
Garbage volumes have decreased.
Years ago it was much more.
People can now already appreciate what is done for them&quot;, says Usov, who has been cleaning beaches for 15 years.
Before, when something new was put up, it was already broken the next day.
Now what is on the beach is kept.
The price of a clean beach
One of the biggest jobs on Estonian beaches is the cleaning of marine litter, or plow, washed ashore.
For example, at Pirita beach, 400,000 tons of it must be transported during the beach season.
&quot;This is an incredible amount,&quot; notes Usov.
Another large category is household waste, i.e. everything that people leave behind.
There are eight large garbage containers on the one-and-a-half-kilometer Stroom beach strip that need to be emptied three times a week.
So much garbage is generated.
However, the cooler summer weather has meant that there is a fifth less litter than usual.
The third type consists of abandoned things.
Mostly these are children&#39;s lives.
As this time&#39;s catch, Usov has scooped out a dozen model cars from the sand.
They will be waiting for their owners on the wooden path leading to the beach.
&quot;Usually more of them come out, but this is a normal catch&quot;. Usov already knows that soon he will find them again in the sand.
Children come to the beach and take toys to sink them in the sand again.
Garbage is scattered
Erika Scholler, representative of Haaberst&#39;s administrative services, admits that the tractor&#39;s sifting work disturbs the locals.
The noise, which lasts from late at night until early morning, disturbs the sleep of people living in the neighborhood.
However, this work is impossible during the day.
The beach must be screened twice in one month.
&quot;If we don&#39;t, the district will fine us,&quot; notes Scholler.
But the goal is to get the Stroom beach under the international blue flag quality mark, just like Pirita, Pikakar and Pärnu.
&quot;Compared to Europe, there is much more work in Estonia to maintain the beaches&quot;, says Scholler.
We have more plow and stones and harder to sift sand.
However, there is less garbage on our beaches than elsewhere in Europe.
Hearing that there is talk of garbage on the beach, Martin, who lives near the Stroom beach, casually enters the conversation between the journalist and the cleaning workers, highlighting the current bottlenecks of the beach.
In the morning, there is an ugly picture everywhere.
The problem is with the birds and the bottle pickers who have pulled the garbage bags inside out,&quot; says Martin.
Although it is difficult to assume that people will be able to change their current behavior, Martin hopes that the city government will do something about the trash cans and, for example, put lids on them to at least prevent birds from exploring there.
Overall, however, Martin is happy with the development of Stroom Beach.
It can be seen that the city is taking care of it.
With children&#39;s playgrounds, lighted and newly asphalted roads, it has become more pleasant.
It used to be that roller skates could only be used on one road&quot;, notes Martin.
Treasure Hunter Finds in Stroom: Coins, Coins Only
40-year-old Dimitri, who combs the beach with a metal detector as a treasure hunter, has had to take advantage of the morning low tide.
He does not believe that he will find anything valuable today or in the future.
The sea gods are not generous enough for that.
&quot;I&#39;ve been working on it for a year and haven&#39;t found anything of value yet,&quot; says Dmitri.
As a hobby treasure hunter, Dmitri has some euro coins, bottle caps and also dangerous nails in his treasure bag, which he later throws in the trash.
There are usually still coins.
&quot;There is usually no gold, rings and the like,&quot; the treasure hunter states.
The Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that interest rates will remain at their previous levels as weak economic growth and easing inflation have dampened speculation about a hike.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish as tightening household incomes have put interest rates on hold.
Policymakers on the Bank&#39;s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer members calling for a hike this month as sluggish economic growth has weakened support for a hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank cut its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and 2018 to 1.6%, and warned that pressure on household incomes would remain as inflation is still expected to rise to close to 3% in the autumn.
At the same time, the bank also signaled that an increase in interest rates is necessary in the next few years to curb inflation caused by Brexit, and a higher-than-expected increase in borrowing costs may be necessary in the financial markets.
Members also voted in favor of a partial withdrawal of the mammoth economic stimulus package launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
The bank will end the Term Funding Scheme, which provides cheap funding to banks, in February, although it said it was now expected to offer £15bn more under the scheme, bringing the total to £115bn.
In the minutes of the decision regarding the rate, the bank says: &quot;In the MPC&#39;s medium forecast, gross domestic product (GDP) will remain weak in the near future, as the difficult situation of real household incomes will continue to have an impact on consumption.&quot;
Regarding the rates, it was reiterated that &quot;some tightening of monetary policy&quot; is necessary to alleviate inflation, and to a &quot;somewhat larger&quot; extent than expected by the markets.
The exchange is currently predicting the first hike in the third quarter of next year and the second hike in 2020.
But the bank stressed that any jumps would be gradual and limited.
The bank&#39;s reduced growth forecasts for this year and next year are comparable to May forecasts of 1.9% and 1.7%.
The forecast of 1.8 percent growth in 2018 remained unchanged.
Following this news, the pound fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to US$1.31 and 0.4% to EUR1.11.
The decision to make no changes is due to recent disappointing growth figures that have dampened rising hopes for a rise, with GDP rising to 0.3% in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months.
The bank says growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will pick up a bit towards the end of the year.
The Bank&#39;s latest inflation report gave households suffering from rising inflation and miserable pay rises little reason to cheer, saying things will get a little worse before they get better.
It was added that monetary policy cannot prevent a blow to incomes in the next few years, but a noticeable recovery of wages is expected towards the end of the three-year forecast.
Due to the weak pound, the economy is also being stimulated by growing demand for British produce, which is partly offsetting lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were raised to 0.25% last August following a shock EU referendum that caused the pound to weaken sharply.
According to the bank, it will likely take four years to fully revive prices and the economy.
Ahead of the bank&#39;s latest decision, there was growing demand for a rate hike as inflation had increased pressure on hard-pressed households; in July, three policymakers called for a rate hike to 0.5%.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month, down from 2.9% in June, although the bank said this was expected and that it is expected to rise again in the coming months.
The bank said the excess growth compared to the 2 percent target was due entirely to the weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, head of mortgage brokers at Coreco, said: “Given the recent fall in exchange rates, the mortgage market looks set to become increasingly competitive again as lenders are eager for work and hope to end the year on a positive note.
The exchange looks particularly favorable for those whose current deals are coming to an end, as refinancing, often with no fees and at low rates, has become increasingly popular.&quot;
The NHS is about to prescribe the controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be able to access a &quot;transformational&quot; HIV prevention treatment from September after a High Court battle over whether the NHS should fund the drug.
NHS England has announced that NHS England is now making pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before intercourse that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in high-risk people by around 86%, to an estimated 10,000 people during an initial three-year clinical trial.
The NHS agreed to fund the clinical trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a High Court ruling last year that the NHS was able to pay for PrEP, despite the agency&#39;s own claims that the drug should be funded by local authorities instead.
NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens hailed the move, unveiled on Thursday, as a &quot;major new intervention&quot;, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a &quot;watershed moment&quot;.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start signing people up. More clinics will be added in October before the program is rolled out across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medication taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Clinical trial results show that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that a person has enough of certain medicines in their body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medicines can be taken every day or no later than two hours before intercourse.
Eligible candidates for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are infected with HIV and cannot receive treatment.
Clinics identify eligible people who agree to participate in a clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people, and those whose HIV-infected partners are not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a family doctor there can also register their wish to participate at a local sexual health clinic participating in the program.
The program costs £10m and NHS England signed a contract to receive the drugs this week following an international tender.
The goal of the clinical trial is to assess PrEP&#39;s true potential by gathering clinical evidence about who the drug is for and how it is consumed and applied in the big picture.
Stevens said: &quot;This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the large-scale and increasingly successful fight against the spread of HIV.
This is another milestone in the more than three-decade-long fight against one of humanity&#39;s biggest health problems.&quot;
Deborah Gold, CEO of NAT, said: “This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if correctly targeted at those who need it and are at risk, has the potential to transform England&#39;s HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV in England will have access to a powerful new tool that is individually managed and not dependent on partner negotiation through this NHS-funded clinical trial, improving many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement.&quot;
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “The priority now is to ensure that the clinical trial across the country is launched quickly and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that the PrEP clinical trial drug has been procured, we are on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.
Shadow Public Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of a PrEP clinical trial is very welcome and long overdue after months of delays and government foot-dragging.
The evidence shows just how much of a difference this drug can make to HIV prevention and ending the spread of this life-changing infection.
This clinical trial brings us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the clinical trial is rolled out across the country as soon as possible to protect people exposed to HIV and bring us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society.&quot;
The price of electricity rose by 12% in Estonia, while it fell in Latvia and Lithuania.
In July, the difference in the next-day exchange price of electricity between the price regions of Estonia and Latvia and Lithuania decreased to 1.94 euros, compared to 7.71 euros in June this year, Elering announced.
The main reason for the price difference is the failure of the Lithuanian-Swedish connection.
In Estonia, the average exchange price of electricity last month was 34.33 euros per megawatt-hour, and the price rose by 12 percent compared to June.
In Latvia and Lithuania, the price dropped by five percent to 36.27 euros per megawatt hour.
In Finland, the price was 34.17 euros, while the Nord Pool system price of the electricity exchange was 26.37 euros per megawatt hour.
Prices rose by 12 and seven percent, respectively.
Electricity moved between Estonia and Finland in 75 percent of the hours last month in the direction of Estonia and in 16 percent of the hours from Estonia to Finland.
In the remaining nine percent of the hours, there were no next-day trades between the two countries.
Between Estonia and Latvia, electricity flowed from Estonia to Latvia 99 percent of the time, and the full transmission capacity was in use in 73 percent of the hours.
According to the transactions that took place on the last trading day of July on the Nasdaq OMX market, the exchange price of electricity in August may be approximately 34 euros and in September 37 euros per megawatt hour.
The price of carbon dioxide, which affects the price of electricity production, rose last month, and transactions took place at a price of 5.04-5.47 euros per ton.
Living the high life - a mezzanine floor and clever design tricks have turned this small Earls Court flat into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker who is a keen property developer, swapped her large Knightsbridge home for a flat in Earls Court in 2014.
It&#39;s on the first floor of Queen Anne Terrace, and it&#39;s a tribute to the new design that Joanne hasn&#39;t packed her bags and resold the flat.
&quot;Before that I was living in a much bigger place in Knightsbridge with my ex-partner,&quot; Joanne said.
“I was looking for something that was equivalent for the price I was offering.
I was shown this flat in Earls Court and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with it and made an offer the same day.&quot;
Since the first visit, this 93 square meter apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
At first, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout - you had to walk through the kitchen to get to the bedroom. Joanne wanted to add storage and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceilings.
&quot;I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,&quot; he said.
He hired Erfan Azad of Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck &amp; Shed to take advantage of the 3.8m high ceilings and create a home that would not just be a development but a place for Joanne to live.
The ceiling wasn&#39;t high enough to add two rooms on top of each other, so it was an architectural challenge to create a mezzanine where you could stand up.
Erfan had to approach the matter creatively.
&quot;The metal structure is quite complex,&quot; he explains.
&quot;We had to rearrange the rooms so that they were on top of each other without having to bend over.
It wasn&#39;t just a case of building a platform, but we used a steel structure so that the height of both the upper and lower rooms was correct.&quot;
This arrangement allowed Erfan to create two full height rooms on top of each other in the space with plenty of dramatic elements.
On the mezzanine floor, a vintage Retrouvius window with copper light opens up to a view of the glamorous living space below.
Golden furniture with a mirror surface, silver details and a retro Serge Mouille lamp emphasize the style of the room.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding theatricality, spaciousness and lightness.
Mirrors have been added at both ends of a short hallway to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the back wall with a mirror gives the impression of a window opening into another room.
At the entrance, a mirrored cabinet provides storage for all of Joanne&#39;s cutlery and glassware.
The ability to close the kitchen area when not in use adds charm to the living room, giving the impression of a more glamorous space.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this kitchen is that it is a garage-type roll-up door.
&quot;It took a bit of design effort,&quot; Erfan explains of the door made of veneered MDF with steel reinforcement.
&quot;It has a counterweight, so it slides very easily when you push it up.&quot;
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage space, Joanne now has 16 extra square meters, an extra bedroom and a better apartment layout.
&quot;At the end of the day, the floor space is what you sell - or what adds value to the property,&quot; says Erfan.
&quot;A real estate agent walks into a room in an outdated form and does calculations based on floor area.&quot;
Here, they have managed to increase the floor area, while using high-quality materials that add luxury to the space.
&quot;Materials are what you touch and thus help create an emotional connection with the home,&quot; says Erfan.
“You don&#39;t fall in love with the electrical wiring in the wall.
It&#39;s important, but it doesn&#39;t make the heart sing.&quot;
It shows that good design and increased area can help turn a fairly ordinary apartment into something amazing.
In fact, they may even make you want to not leave, as Joanne did.
The main character, Dane Jensen, is a bounty hunter working in a Chicago skyscraper who competes with a colleague for a promotion.
Nothing matters but the amount of money earned, next to which all ethics are forgotten.
The man sees his wife and three children only in the early morning and late at night.
In the first half of the film, I catch myself thinking that this is the business world version of &quot;House of Cards&quot; - even Kevin Spacey and Gerard Butler&#39;s speech style is similar.
As the film goes on, however, the camera element becomes less and less, and the moralizing intention of the filmmakers becomes more and more apparent.
The main character&#39;s son gets cancer as a life-changing experience.
Now you have to make a choice between work and family life.
A son who dreams of becoming an architect makes his father think about really important things such as faith, kindness, love... during his walks to the big buildings of Chicago, not even the disaster of the Twin Towers remains untouched.
After the third scene, where the son opens his father&#39;s eyes, one gets the feeling that the filmmakers have set the goal of making the audience cry, because even the hardest-hearted viewer can&#39;t hold back tears when seeing the suffering of a cute boy with cancer.
When his son falls into a coma and his situation seems hopeless, the father finally understands the morality of his work and does a good deed for an old man looking for work.
Now I make a bet with myself in my mind - if the movie has a happy ending, I will reward my perspicacity with a coffee after the movie, but if I&#39;m wrong, the screenwriter can be praised for at least one surprise.
For a moment there is a doubt that I will miss the coffee - when my husband calls Dane from the hospital and he rushes in slow motion along the corridor towards the ward.
However, the son has miraculously recovered, and even though his father has just lost his job, this also turns out to be positive, because now he has time to deal with the family.
I can feel good too - I can already predict the end of the American drama quite well!
To be honest, the film is well constructed, all the necessary elements are there.
You can cry, you can laugh, the actors are good and the moral is beautiful: money is not the most important thing in life.
I guess this movie will bring in well.
Trump&#39;s new chief of staff plans to limit the president&#39;s media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really pull it off.
In that case, he would be the first.
Politico reports that the White House&#39;s new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information, including news, to President Trump in the hope that it will keep the boss on a level playing field.
Here&#39;s an excerpt from reporter Josh Dawsey:
&quot;When new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with senior officials on his first day on the job, he outlined a key problem in President Donald Trump&#39;s White House that he planned to address: bad information getting into the hands of the president.
Kelly told officials that information had to flow through him, either on paper or in meetings, because the president would make better decisions if he was given good information.&quot;
Kelly&#39;s diagnosis seems perfectly logical, but others have tried and failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media consumption.
President Trump&#39;s relationship with television goes back decades, and even now that he&#39;s in the White House, his TV viewing habits haven&#39;t gone away.
&quot;When candidate Trump was upset about unfair media coverage, it was worth showing him that he was also being fairly covered by influential outlets,&quot; former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico&#39;s Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that &quot;the key to controlling Trump&#39;s Twitter habits is making sure his personal media consumption includes a steady stream of eulogies, according to six former campaign staffers.&quot;
OK.
But the idea that Trump&#39;s Twitter habits were ever &quot;under control&quot; is ludicrous.
Perhaps these campaign workers know something the rest of us don&#39;t — that Trump&#39;s tweets would have been even more inflammatory without their intervention.
We&#39;ll probably never know about the tweets Trump didn&#39;t post.
If his assistants managed to save him from trouble a few times, their efforts were worth it.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from constantly creating controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House made up of competing cliques, people are exclusively trying to advance their own interests by feeding Trump material that supports their worldview, but may not always be reliable.
Covering the whole story, Politico wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to feed the president information of questionable strategic value.
One of the examples described by reporter Shane Goldmacher is as follows:
&quot;Current and former Trump subordinates say Trump can react explosively to negative press, particularly damaging leaks, with an obsession with identifying their source.
That&#39;s what happened in late February, when someone gleefully gave the president a printed copy of an article from GotNews.com, owned by internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the &quot;source of multiple leaks&quot; at the White House.
It doesn&#39;t matter that Johnson has been permanently banned from Twitter for taunting, or that he didn&#39;t offer any concrete evidence, or that he&#39;s made and retracted false accusations in the past.
Trump read the article and began asking subordinates about Walsh.&quot;
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Chief of Staff Rob Porter &quot;have been trying to establish a system for managing and documenting documents that reach Trump.&quot;
How did it work out?
Kelly tries to do the exact same thing three months later.
He may prove to be a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his aides are still vying for influence.
These immutable factors make Kelly&#39;s mission very difficult.
Street musicians who came to the capital from abroad do not hesitate to get a permit to perform.
Many foreigners go to play music in the center of Tallinn.
Those with whom Õhtuleht spoke admitted that they play in the old town without the permission of the city government.
We were the first to find three street musicians near the gates of Viru, who had brought as many dogs with them.
It was clear that the musicians in dreadlocks and tattered clothes were backpackers who could use one shower to kill them.
