Eesti Pank bought bonds for 149 million euros in July as part of the public sector asset purchase program of the euro area central banks, the bond portfolio of the central bank grew to 4.36 billion euros.
The Central Bank does not publish more detailed information about purchases.
The president of the Bank of Estonia, Hardo Hansson, has previously explained in response to the questioning of members of the Riigikogu that the asset purchase program of the Eurosystem central banks includes three different purchase programs: covered bonds of the financial sector, asset-backed bonds (ABS) and public sector bonds (PSPP).
The central bank buys bonds from the market in order to encourage investors who sold bonds to invest their money elsewhere.
As a result of the purchases, the return on lower-risk assets falls and this motivates investors to take greater risks.
As a general rule, within the public sector bond purchase program, each central bank buys government bonds of its own country, bonds of other countries are not bought.
Since the Estonian state has not issued bonds, Eesti Pank makes so-called replacement purchases within the limits of the amount allocated to them.
Replacement purchases are also made by central banks in those countries where the supply of bonds corresponding to the purchasing plan is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally buys bonds of European institutions, such as the bonds of the European Financial Stability Fund and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank has been buying bonds as part of the asset purchase program since March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering&#39;s bonds were also acquired, but from June 2016, Eesti Pank no longer buys Elering&#39;s bonds.
Starting in June, the Central Bank of Finland will buy both Elering and Eesti Energia bonds on behalf of the euro area central banks.
