The journalist&#39;s murder underscores the growing danger in Mexico
The staff of the weekly Riodoce usually gathers on Wednesdays to review plans to cover the latest chaos in the state of Sinaloa, which is being sown by organized crime, corrupt officials and relentless drug wars.
But today, in the shadow of a personal tragedy, they have gathered to discuss their own safety.
They are told that it is important to change their routines.
Two senior journalists discuss which seems safer: bringing the children with them to the office, which was the target of a grenade attack in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a blackboard at the front of the room: &quot;enemies,&quot; &quot;neutrals,&quot; &quot;allies.&quot;
They ask reporters to provide names for each column—no proof needed, just impressions and gut feelings.
Drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen and journalists are suspected of being in the employ of the government or cartels - a whole list of bad guys who make it dangerous to cover the chaos in Mexico.
There is no respite from the violence, and the more bodies pile up across the country, the greater the number of journalists - according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, there have been at least 25 since the inauguration of President Enrique Pena Nieto in December 2012. 589 journalists are under national protection after attacks and threats and at least seven journalists in seven states have been killed so far this year.
The latest casualties include their editor and inspiration, Riodoce co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
&quot;The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,&quot; Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug violence.
His absence is deeply felt, although his presence can be felt everywhere - a large picture of Valdez showing the middle finger with the words &quot;Justice&quot; hangs on the facade of the Riodoce building, and two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts depicting him smiling with glasses face or his characteristic panama hat.
The meeting comes less than two months after his death. Reporters discuss shared trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a separate state prosecutor&#39;s office was created in 2010 to handle cases of journalists, according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, only two cases have been prosecuted.
As is the case with most of the annual drug-trafficking and organized crime murders, which number in the thousands, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
The Riodoce editorial continues to cover the violence in Sinaloa, though their hearts are broken and the landscape is now even more dangerous.
Without data and justice for the killers, Ibarra said, the security meeting is of little use.
&quot;It&#39;s very silly to waste your time in this meeting,&quot; he says.
&quot;Until the reason is known, you distrust everyone.&quot;
Valdez left Riodoce&#39;s office in Culiacan, the state capital, on the morning of May 15.
He only managed to drive a few blocks before two men stopped him in a red Toyota Corolla. He was forced out of the car and shot 12 times. This is presumably because of the newspaper&#39;s name, which translates as &quot;twelfth river&quot;.
The gunman drove off in Valdez&#39;s car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He is survived by his wife and two adult children.
Rumors run wild in Culiacan.
But there is mostly silence on the subject of Valdez.
Since Guzman&#39;s arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has been one of the country&#39;s bloodiest battlegrounds as rival cliques battle to fill the power vacuum.
It doesn&#39;t matter that a person or several are gunned down every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the graveyard is teeming with lavishly decorated double mausoleums of drug lords larger than the homes of many living.
Let&#39;s forget for a moment that peacetime refers to a single cartel running a maritime state with valuable ports and drug routes to the United States.
Despite all this, and the fact that Valdez was fully aware of the dangers of his job, Riodoce co-founder and manager Ismail Bojorquez, 60, feels immense guilt that he failed to protect his friend.
He believes two mistakes contributed to the killing.
The first was the publication in February of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the frontman of the warring cartel clique that rivals Guzman&#39;s sons.
The piece must have angered the boys - suspected gang members bought up all the copies of the publication as soon as they hit the newsstands.
Another mistake was that Valdez was not forced to leave the country for his own safety after another newsroom covering the same story was raided.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a turning point in violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would be around forever.
He was working as a veteran reporter for the Noroeste newspaper in 2003 when he joined five colleagues to create Riodoce, selling $50 units.
Bojorquez said that in Sinaloa &quot;it was impossible to do journalism without touching the drug problem.&quot;
Over time, the newspaper gained recognition for its bold and honest coverage, and sales and advertising grew.
Reporters liked to publish robust research without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by print, where they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after Riodoce was founded, the newspaper won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for its coverage of Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists (AKK) for his courage in following the Mexican drug story wherever it leads.
He openly admitted that he was afraid.
&quot;I want to live on,&quot; he said when accepting the AKK award.
In an interview with Rompeviento TV last October, he said that drug trafficking is a way of life in Sinaloa.
&quot;You have to accept the task that comes with being a journalist - the other option is to play dumb.
I don&#39;t want to be asked what I did in the face of so many deaths or why I didn&#39;t tell what was going on.&quot;
The Riodoce collective misses Valdez, the joker who snarled like a sailor, the friend who kindly shared hugs and advice, the teacher who knew how to survive.
They relied on his routine.
He always wore his hat.
He went to the El Guayabo bar across the street from the office and always sat at the same table.
Now they ask if his routine love proved fatal for him.
His death has also made them question themselves, how to do their job best and stay alive.
&quot;They don&#39;t like you messing with their women, their children, their legitimate businesses, their secret landing sites used to transport drugs.&quot;
&quot;These things were not to be touched,&quot; Bojorquez said.
The result is strong self-censorship and self-preservation even in the best of times.
Trusting your instincts.
If something smells fishy, stay away.
According to Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal, the problem is that &quot;the sense of smell can be deceived... and that&#39;s what happened with Javier.&quot;
He and others say the old rules no longer apply in Sinaloa, just as they don&#39;t in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt government officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
Cell phones were suddenly not allowed in the room where Riodoce employees met for security training; a few days before that, it was revealed that spyware sold exclusively to governments had been used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
In front of the house, two policemen sought relief from the 40-degree heat in the shade of a tree.
The government assigned them to guard Riodoce&#39;s office, located in a four-story building in a middle-class neighborhood in Culiacan.
Some reporters half-jokingly wondered if these police officers were among the 50 percent of police officers the governor himself has labeled as untrustworthy.
Several months have passed since reporters have traveled to the mountainous countryside where control is de facto in the hands of drug gangs.
This week&#39;s edition of Riodoce covered three main stories.
One of them was the murder of former boxing legend Julio Cesar Chavez&#39;s brother in Sinaloa.
In addition, they had a revealing story about spending government money on the governor&#39;s home town.
And one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block away from the prosecutor&#39;s office, was robbed by a group of people.
There was no official announcement of who was robbed or how it happened, so caution had to be taken when it came time to write what everyone in town knows - the restaurant is a hot spot for drug dealers and authorities alike.
The reporter learned from public records that the restaurant is registered in the name of a politician who belongs to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (IRP), which dominated all levels of politics for almost the entire last century.
Recently, several IRP governors have been accused of corruption in high-profile court cases.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents at the same location, including how the son of Guzman, nicknamed El Chapo, escaped a military raid.
Just a few months ago, readers would have turned to Valdez&#39;s column for the best sources of kidnapping information.
&quot;Before, we would have already known what happened,&quot; said the 46-year-old Villarreal, whose diminutive frame has earned him the nickname El Flaco.
&quot;Now all channels of communication with our sources have been cut off.&quot;
Valdez&#39;s office has become a storage room for signs and stickers protesting the killing of journalists, and the editorial staff has become something they never expected—activists for the press.
Reporter Miriam Ramirez grabbed a few signs and headed to the local prosecutor&#39;s office the next morning to protest yet another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the western state of Michoacán three days after Valdez was killed.
A burned body has been found and officials say it belongs to him based on DNA tests.
Journalists across the country have become more vocal, scrawling the phrase &quot;SOS press&quot; on sidewalks and buildings as an organized protest.
That day, Chief Bojorquez is away in Washington, D.C., trying to rally international support for justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa a day after Valdez&#39;s death, Ramirez accused authorities of spying on journalists and killing them for telling the truth.
After that, he asked to be diverted from covering government activities, worried that the anger had affected his objectivity.
Valdez had repeatedly said that Mexican journalists were &quot;confined&quot; by organized crime, complicit government officials and an indifferent society.
In his latest book &quot;Drug Journalism&quot;, he wrote that reporters are not only killed by drug gangs, but also at the behest of politicians and security forces, who are allied with organized crime.
Media monitoring group Articulo 19 attributed more than half of attacks on journalists last year to police and government officials.
&quot;In Mexico, you die because they want to silence you,&quot; Ramirez said.
The murders are obviously chilling.
No one will forget the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias in the northern border state of Tamaulipas six years ago.
His body was found with a note, believed to have been signed by the Los Zetas cartel: &quot;I&#39;m here for my reporting.&quot;
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to his severed head.
Some publications have decided to close their doors, such as the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua, after the killing of their correspondent Miroslava Breach in March.
Others let it go, as the newspaper El Manana de Nuevo Laredo did after the assassination of their editor in 2004.
In 2010, the newspaper Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed the drug cartels with a front-page editorial, &quot;What do you want from us?&quot;.
Some journalists have fled their home states or even the country.
It is a nerve-wracking decision.
It is hard to find work in exile and they still have to pick the streets to avoid danger.
And sometimes they are pursued, as is believed to have happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered along with four women in a Mexico City apartment in 2015, three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay put and continue to work have to dance around risky decisions every day.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits that covering the drug business scares him.
&quot;Mexico is on its way to hell, and that&#39;s why I became a reporter,&quot; he said.
At midnight on a recent Friday, with the latest issue already locked, Riodoce&#39;s editors were sitting on the sidewalk outside the office sipping beer when suddenly everyone&#39;s phones started vibrating.
In the coastal resort town of Mazatlan, 19 people were confirmed dead in the exchange of fire between rival gangs and security forces.
The war continued to escalate, as promised by several messages left by cartels found in the region.
From the side of the sidewalk, reporters posted the news on the Riodoce website using their cell phones.
The next day&#39;s front cover needed a change.
Sirens blared by - another exchange of fire in the area.
Bojorquez peered at the officers on duty to see if they were alert.
If they were afraid, they didn&#39;t show it in the least.
Beneath a massive portrait of the newspaper&#39;s fallen founder, with his middle finger visible to all of Sinaloa, Riodoce workers followed in his footsteps.
&quot;How could you even think about closure,&quot; Bojorquez said, &quot;when on the same day Javier was killed, an intern asked me to send him out into the streets to report?&quot;
The dinosaur used protective color to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a rather scary one.
Scientists have now revealed the first findings of an incredible rhinoceros-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner that is so well preserved that experts have described it as the &quot;Mona Lisa of dinosaurs&quot;.
In fact, it is so well preserved that it was even possible to identify that his scaled skin was a reddish-brown color and that he had had a somewhat &quot;complicated&quot; past.
A report in the journal Current Biology described the creature as &quot;the best-preserved pangolins ever found&quot; and &quot;one of the finest dinosaur specimens in the world&quot;.
The fossil is a new species of nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, 110-112 million years ago.
Its incredible preservation has amazed researchers, who describe it as &quot;truly remarkable&quot;.
This scaly herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its type ever found, according to National Geographic magazine.
It was found on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk while mining at the Suncor Millenium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that didn&#39;t resemble the surrounding rock and decided to investigate further.
The discovered fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The next six years were spent working to excavate the animal from the 2,500-pound (1,100-kilogram) piece of land.
After all this hard work, the end result is now finally ready to be released to the public.
&quot;If you squint a little, you can almost believe it&#39;s sleeping,&quot; said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
&quot;It will go down in scientific history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.&quot;
Examining its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, although covered in scales and resembling a walking tank, was probably significantly threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
This heavily armored dinosaur used red and white protective coloring to hide from predators and employed a camouflage technique called counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
According to experts, this allowed the dinosaur to better blend into its surroundings and avoid enemies, as larger dinosaurs were likely to hunt it.
This 110-million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Scientists have now studied the creature and named it Borealopelta after Mark Mitchell Museum lab technician Mark Mitchell, who was part of the team that spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly uncovering the animal.
Thanks to the specimen&#39;s amazing preservation, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of researchers were able to document the shape and size of the scales on the animal&#39;s body.
They discovered counter-eclipsing, a common defense method in the animal kingdom that means the top half of the creature was darker than the bottom.
Although counter-eclipsing is common, the findings come as a surprise, as Borealopelta is much larger than the counter-eclipsing animals living today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was hunted actively enough by other carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favored hiding over confrontation as a survival tactic.
However, most modern animals that use counter-shadowing - such as deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that Nodosaurus had to really struggle to survive.
&quot;The vigorous hunting of an enormously large and heavily armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous Cretaceous dinosaur predators could have been,&quot; Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur&#39;s skin was reddish brown.
Scientists are continuing to study the animal for clues about its life, including the preserved contents of its gut to find out what the animal ate for its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river when it died, thus reaching the sea with the current, where it sank back to the bottom of the ocean.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans likely extended much further inland than they do today.
&quot;This nodosaurus is truly remarkable because it is completely covered in preserved scaly skin, while also remaining three-dimensional, preserving the animal&#39;s original shape,&quot; Brown said.
&quot;As a result, the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the Cretaceous.
You don&#39;t have to use a lot of imagination to reconstruct it - it&#39;s enough to squint your eyes and it looks like he&#39;s sleeping.&quot;
The Cretaceous period was a time when huge bipedal carnivorous dinosaurs - theropods - roamed the Earth.
Although the king of them all, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of its fearsome predecessors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, a monster that was 38 feet (11.5 meters) long and weighed six tons.
The researchers, whose recent findings are published in the journal Current Biology, believe Borealopelta was washed into the sea after death and mummified in the mud.
The creature was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk while mining at the Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and scales, and is complete from snout to hips.
These creatures averaged 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
Two 20-inch spikes protruded from its shoulders.
Scientists believe this scaled herbivore roamed what is now western Canada until a flooded river washed it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur&#39;s underwater burial helped to preserve its scales in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the ridged plates of armor along the dinosaur&#39;s skull are still covered by remnants of skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic magazine: “This degree of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more incredible it seems.
Fossilized remains of skin still cover the humped scales on the animal&#39;s skull.
The right front leg is lying next to him, with five toes extended upwards.
I can count the scales on his soles.&quot;
How one activist found the answer to the question &quot;Whose streets?&quot;
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell got a complete shock.
Just a day after traveling to New York, it sat in St. Louis resident on his bed in a room rented through Airbnb, scrolling through Facebook on his phone.
He came across a post from his former schoolmate.
It read: &quot;An 18-year-old has just been killed by the police and is still lying in the street.&quot;
Confused as to why no one else had posted this information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
The posts of the user with the handle @TheePharoah were repeatedly reshared on his timeline.
St. Louis-area rapper live-tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
She posted a picture of Brown&#39;s lifeless body lying in the street, where it remained for four hours.
&quot;This is crazy,&quot; Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to him or his community.
He put his phone away, only to see the tweets again later in the evening, this time announcing a gathering of people on Canfield Drive.
Photos were shared of police tape and people screaming, and a man claiming to be Brown&#39;s father holding a sign reading &quot;Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!&quot;.
He watched a live feed of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another police officer, he said, pointed a gun and yelled, &quot;I&#39;m going to kill all of you ... animals.&quot;
Ferrell remembers thinking, &quot;This is unusual.&quot;
&quot;This is not the kind of murder we are used to and what we would call typical.&quot;
I felt a shiver of fear at that moment.
I was angry and I cried.&quot;
He booked a return flight and drove home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., he went to his father&#39;s house to pick up his six-year-old daughter and decided that the two of them would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the focus of the new documentary Whose Streets? (&quot;Whose streets?&quot;), which premieres in theaters on August 11.
It&#39;s a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and toughness, from the perspective of the people who live in this community and who filled the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell and his daughter - wearing a floral dress and matching crown - drove to Ferguson, they again talked about a topic that had come up many times before that morning - the experience and living conditions of black people.
&quot;Remember when I taught you how the black community had to fight for their rights?&quot; he recalls asking himself.
&quot;We&#39;re going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that&#39;s not right.&quot;
&quot;I couldn&#39;t not take him,&quot; Ferrell said later.
“What is happening now is… the culmination of what happened in the past.
