Startups that can help your business avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but surveys were fruitless.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful or, even worse, misleading.
And even when he promised anonymity, some employees didn&#39;t trust the process.
&quot;The system just wasn&#39;t consistent and objective,&quot; said Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a San Francisco-based hair care e-commerce company with 75 employees.
So he called in outsiders for help.
A new breed of HR startups is emerging to help companies figure out what their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software specifically designed to measure employee engagement, they enable companies to conduct snap surveys, target specific teams and demographics, provide employee anonymity and a grievance hotline, and in some cases allow native speakers to bypass C-level executives and reach out to directly to the board.
&quot;Now there are tools like Strava and Fitbit for health tracking, but where is Fitbit for your business?&quot; asked Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Glint, a Redwood City startup that uses software analytics tools for companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett says that in the three years he&#39;s been using Glint, he&#39;s gained a much better understanding of what his employees are thinking and feeling.
In addition to ad hoc surveys and surveys of specific teams, it provides a company heat map that provides insight into which departments have the most complaints and which managers have the lowest support, allowing him to identify the reasons.
Companies are beginning to realize they need to stay on top of their work culture to avoid becoming the next Uber, which has been embroiled in scandal since a former employee published a blog post describing a harassing environment where those who dared to speak out were punished.
For startups like Glint, the desire to have insight is a lucrative business opportunity.
The global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020, according to financial technology statistics website Let&#39;s Talk Payments.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, has seen an uptick in interest and activity this year amid Uber&#39;s dubious reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a customer.
Like Glintki, Convercent lets companies send customized impulse surveys, collect confidential responses in real-time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous message line that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
And when the CEO is involved, complaints go directly to the board.
&quot;Public opinion has been usurped by regulators,&quot; said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
Quinlan said that if a company is found to be mistreating its employees or behaving unethically, the company could face serious consequences, such as consumer boycotts, walkouts and lawsuits, even if regulators don&#39;t get involved.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees at 500 locations, has used Convercent for more than a year to ensure employee awareness of policies and procedures and provide an easy way to communicate with corporate headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, they had to find a phone number or email address at corporate headquarters, file a formal complaint, and hope it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frustrating and awkward process, said Ruby Tuesday general counsel James Vitrano, who said there was no good way to track employee complaints.
However, now that the company uses Convercent, issues such as discrimination, harassment or unfair pay practices that previously did not reach managers operating in offices in other cities or states can be identified and addressed more quickly.
&quot;I&#39;m able to get closer to the holistic 360-degree experience of employees,&quot; said Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday&#39;s risk management group.
&quot;And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees.&quot;
Quinlan said that companies began to take ethical behavior, values and employee engagement much more seriously in 2002, after the auditing firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations related to the Enron scandal.
But it wasn&#39;t until &quot;social media came of age&quot; that companies realized they couldn&#39;t stop their dirty laundry from being aired publicly online.
&quot;Before using technology to monitor ethical behavior, people used hope as a strategy,&quot; he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a periodic fee for using their products.
It&#39;s a business model and opportunity that has the approval of venture capital investors who have backed both startups.
Convercent received $10 million in funding in February from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the capital raised to $47 million.
Glint received a $10 million investment from Bessemer Venture Partners in November, bringing the company&#39;s total funding to $60 million.
Such investments do not come as a surprise when you consider the interconnectedness of companies, culture and venture capital.
More and more research shows that today&#39;s workers expect more from the workplace than ever before.
In highly competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are mere table stakes.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
&quot;When people are happy at a company, feel listened to and that the work they do is rewarding, they are more committed to the company&#39;s success,&quot; said Nina McQueen, vice president of overall benefits and employee experience at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn income when their portfolio companies do well; companies do well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and engagement, it&#39;s no wonder they&#39;re gaining traction.
Having data on employee engagement is important, according to work culture experts.
But that data is useless if the company&#39;s watchdogs don&#39;t act on it.
In fact, when a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can create expectations that changes are coming.
And if change doesn&#39;t happen fast enough or not at all, it can lead to frustration and reduced employee engagement.
&quot;If you ask for 4,000 proposals, you need to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,&quot; said Russell Raath, president of consulting and business management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
&quot;Because if you don&#39;t get things done, employees will think, &#39;Did you actually listen to me?&#39;
do you care
And if you don&#39;t care, why should I?&#39;&#39;
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly employee surveys, has been able to take action the same day the problem is reported through Glint.
And after receiving feedback from employees frustrated with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, he was able to reorganize several teams in the company and provide communication training to address the issues.
However, Ruby Tuesdays collects new employee data and hopes that, in the long run, it will lead to longer-term employee engagement in an industry known for its high labor turnover.
&quot;If you&#39;re not committed to transparency, you&#39;re going to lose people,&quot; Vitrano said.
“And if you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose businesses.&quot;
