The rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the draft law amending the Act on the Release of Genetically Modified Organisms into the Environment (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act for approval.
The amendment to the law waives the creation of a separate database for the locations and handlers of genetically modified (GM) crops, and the plant health register will be used for this purpose in the future.
In addition, the obligation of the operator of the GM crop to have a prior agreement with the person engaged in beekeeping within the prescribed radius is changed.
Although genetically modified crops are not grown in Estonia at the moment, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-genetically modified crops.
At least until it is decided to declare Estonia GMO-free&quot;, said Sigmar Suu, head of the plant health department of the Ministry of Agriculture.
&quot;At the same time, it must be taken into account that the developed measures must be goal-oriented and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burden for both the private and public sectors&quot;, added Suu.
The draft law repeals the provisions related to the database of locations and handlers of GM crops and handling training in GMOVS, and establishes the requirements for handling GM crops and starting economic activities.
Specifically in relation to beekeeping, the previous obligation of the GM crop grower to inform the beekeepers about starting the cultivation of the GM crop will be replaced by the obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before starting the cultivation.
The draft law has been sent to the ministries for coordination.
All interested parties have the opportunity to familiarize themselves with it in the draft information system and, if they wish, submit their opinion to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes primarily affect persons operating in the field of crop production, beekeepers and the Board of Agriculture.
In the European Union, including Estonia, it is allowed to grow only one GM crop - corn MON 810.
So far, however, none of the Estonian farmers are interested in growing GM crops.
The reason is that there is no corn pest in Estonia, the European stem borer, to which the corn line MON 810 is resistant.
Also, the varieties of this corn line have been bred for southern regions and this corn is not suitable for our climate.
In order to obtain the above certainty, the Ministry of Rural Affairs has commissioned studies in 2015 and 2016 to detect possible contamination with GM organisms in the seeds of various rapeseed, corn and soy varieties grown in Estonia.
The analysis results of the samples taken showed that the seeds did not contain foreign genes, and as a result of the study it was concluded that the seeds of rapeseed, corn and soy varieties grown in Estonia do not contain genetically modified organisms.
In turn, it can be concluded from the above that genetically modified crops are not deliberately grown in Estonia, and it was also confirmed that there has been no accidental contamination.
