The White House exhibit cost taxpayers thousands
The White House&#39;s decision to fly a Navy helicopter into the South Yard last month for an event celebrating American manufacturing cost taxpayers a whopping $24,000, according to military documents released to TIME.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, called Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event showcasing America&#39;s construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured industrial products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-built helicopter was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire engine from Wisconsin and a forklift made in Mississippi.
According to documents from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the squadron responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House War Office requested the helicopter&#39;s presence with a partial command, or FARGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Yard for an &quot;unusual&quot; event.
&quot;I wanted you to be aware of this because it is an unusually high-profile event,&quot; HMX-1&#39;s commanding officer said in an email the day before the event to his superior, the Navy&#39;s deputy commanding officer for aviation.
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive at the south yard around 7 a.m. on July 17 for an event starting at 3 p.m. and would remain there until the yard was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. that evening.
Added was the fact that if the departure from the White House were to be delayed, another crew would be needed for the return flight due to time constraints.
The original aircrew was with the helicopter during the event and the squadron&#39;s security team remained close to the aircraft throughout its time on the ground.
From the documents provided to TIME magazine, it was not possible to determine whether a second crew was needed in the end or not.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
The documents show that HMX-1 investigated whether this event might violate that provision.
&quot;We asked if this violated the Hatch Act and were told it did not,&quot; the commander wrote.
&quot;Looks like you don&#39;t have a choice,&quot; replied the deputy commanding officer.
The White House declared the event an official &quot;Made in America&quot; event and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political undertones.
At the event, the president supported the health care reform efforts being debated in the Senate at the time and praised efforts to keep government regulations in check.
The use of an aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically profitable purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must use them for travel.
However, the requirement to use them purely for a photo shoot is unusual.
Trump came under fire in February when the presidential jet rolled into the background at his first campaign event in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account has been abuzz with messages complaining about his predecessor&#39;s use of the presidential jet.
&quot;The White House is very pleased with the ``Made in America&#39;&#39; display, which featured products from all 50 states, made with American materials by American workers,&quot; said Acting White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often conduct test flights around Washington, D.C. and in the South Yard to practice landing the President of the United States at the White House with centimeter accuracy.
While Trump was in Germany for the G20 summit in early July, HMX-1 made 58 test landings in the White House courtyard.
According to the official, the flight to the &quot;Made in America&quot; event was included in the flight crew&#39;s norm for that month&#39;s training flights.
The squadron&#39;s helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day for &quot;non-presidential support missions.&quot;
According to the White House, no other exhibit at the event burdened the taxpayer&#39;s wallet.
According to a representative of Sikorsky, the company was not involved in organizing the display of the helicopter in the southern yard.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records of presidential flights, and it is difficult to ascertain the exact costs incurred by the event.
But according to the Ministry of Defense&#39;s 2017 financial year hourly rates, the compensation rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The squadron&#39;s records listed the flight from its home base at Naval Air Station Quantico, Virginia, as 30 minutes each way.
The White House says the actual cost of using the helicopter is well below that amount.
&quot;Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on estimated reimbursement rates is very misleading,&quot; Walters said.
&quot;These estimated reimbursement rates include staffing, maintenance and many other sunk costs that are factored into the annual appropriations.&quot;
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs, but they do cover costs related to fuel, maintenance and contracts.
Former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter at the event at the time.
&quot;The point is to showcase things made in America this week,&quot; Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contribution to our national security and that there are probably hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I believe that, just like most Americans, we are all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
So of course it&#39;s right to highlight it.&quot;
It is not clear whether or not Trump came into contact with the helicopter while touring the South Yard as part of the event, but he did get behind the wheel of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives, joking to media outlets about the company&#39;s products in his personal fleet of aircraft.
&quot;I know Sikorsky very well,&quot; said the president, &quot;I have three of their products.&quot;
