Did PSG warn Barcelona about approaching Neymar three years ago?
La Liga may regret their interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain are not giving up in their bid to lure Neymar to their ranks, making a £189m bid to buy him out. But did they warn Barcelona of this record-breaking conquest three years ago?
The high-profile approach has opened the summer transfer window, with the Ligue 1 club poised to more than double the current world record for over-buying, set last season by Paul Pogba&#39;s £89m return to Manchester United.
Once the transfer is completed, Neymar will become the world&#39;s most expensive player as well as the highest paid professional athlete in the world, earning over £500,000 a week after payments from PSG.
Barcelona are known to be angry at both the approach and the release of Neymar, although a source close to the Catalans board confirms that the club has always taken the best care of the footballer since his arrival from Santos in 2013.
But did the PSG president warn the football world of such a possibility three years ago?
When Manchester City showed interest in signing Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi issued a stern warning to any clubs thinking of signing some of PSG&#39;s best players.
&quot;I&#39;m not worried because they know that if they touch any of our players, we will confront them and contact those players,&quot; Al-Khelaifi said.
&quot;We respect all clubs.
But if they try to sign any of our players, they will have to face the consequences.&quot;
Barcelona appear to have crossed that line, with the Spanish club showing interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG have made it clear that they will not let the Italian leave under any circumstances and that Barcelona could be hit back as a result of this interest by losing one of their prized assets in the form of Neymar.
PM: Ireland wants to build bridges, not borders after Brexit.
&quot;Brexit seriously threatens to drive a wedge between Northern Ireland and Ireland, between Britain and Ireland,&quot; Varadkar warned on his first visit to Northern Ireland since taking office in June.
&quot;I can&#39;t imagine who would benefit from it,&quot; he added.
Cross-border infrastructure projects made the current free movement of people and goods possible, Varadkar said.
&quot;This is our vision for the future: to build bridges, not borders&quot;, he emphasized.
According to Varadkar, he would prefer Britain to remain part of the European Union, and since that is not possible, to remain part of the European Common Market.
This would maintain the current free trade between the Republic of Ireland and the United Kingdom.
Another way to make Britain&#39;s departure smoother would be to create a customs union between the European Union and the United Kingdom, explained the Irish Prime Minister.
Noting that such an arrangement existed with Turkey, Varadkar said: &quot;We could certainly have one with Britain&quot;.
The alternative would be a return to customs points that herald historical division and political failure.
&quot;A barrier to trade, prosperity and peace,&quot; said the Irish Prime Minister.
He called Brexit &quot;the challenge of our generation&quot; and warned that its outcome could affect every aspect of daily life in Northern Ireland.
The Irish Prime Minister met with the leaders of the main parties in Northern Ireland during a visit to Belfast.
Märt Avand, who completed his first half-length triathlon: Anyone can complete an Ironman.
Today, the biggest triathlon festival in the Baltic States was held in the winter capital Otepää, when approximately one thousand triathletes from over thirty countries took part in the half-length Ironman competition.
The 70.3 mile distance consisted of a 1.9 km swim, a 90 km bike ride and a 21.1 km bike ride.
Among others, Märt Avandi also finished the first triathlon of his life victoriously.
&quot;I thought it would turn out to be difficult, and in the end it was,&quot; Avandi said at the finish.
Despite the complexity, Avandi recognized that, in fact, triathlon is affordable for almost everyone.
&quot;It&#39;s not the distance that kills, but the pace,&quot; he said, hinting that almost anyone can reach the finish line at a reasonable pace.
Except for Ott Sepp: &quot;Ot&#39;s physique is fine, but unfortunately he can&#39;t swim&quot;.
Avandi had been training hard since February.
At first 4-5 hours a week, but later already ten hours a week.
With a time of 05:34:12, he took 270th place overall.
Although Avandi lost to both Raio Piiroja (time 04:59:53) and Jürgen Lig (time 05:06:37), he beat other competitors in the so-called &quot;prominent class&quot;.
Tanel Padar, who was a &quot;good role model&quot; last year, lost to Avandi by seven minutes (time 05:41:54), journalist Sten Teppan by 16 minutes (time 05:50:23), Kalev Kruus and Raivo E. Tamm by approximately an hour (times respectively 06 :31:53 and 06:45:18).
German Johannes Moldan was crowned the overall winner of the men&#39;s competition of the Otepää stage, which is part of the Ironman series, with a time of 3:58:27, and Ivo Suur was the best of the Estonians with a time of 04:14:09.
Among the women, Helle Frederiksen from Denmark won with a time of 04:24:01, while Maria Jänese from Estonia, who lost to Frederiksen by almost half an hour and clocked 04:58:58.
Avanti completed the 1.9 km swimming distance in 42 minutes and 14 seconds.
He came out of the water in 410th position.
